reviews_data.review_text:
I really didn't want to write this review.

I've been to Summit plenty of times over the past several years - probably since their inception - in fact, we used to buy Summit coffee in bulk for events years ago, and despite the poor quality of that coffee, this review will only pertain to this coffeeshop in Huntersville.

Summit coffee has consistently provided boring, bland, and awful tasting coffee throughout every visit I've had to this coffeeshop. The espresso is overextracted and violently bitter, while the filter coffee is weak, tasting more of commodity-grade coffee with unsweetened cherry flavor added to it. I have never had a good cup of coffee from Summit.

I get it though, the vibes are nice, it's a good place to hang out or study or work, I suppose. But I can do that many other places and enjoy much better coffee while doing so.

Staff is generally friendly enough, but baristas and hosts rarely have a deep knowledge or understanding of the roasts they are serving. Summit seems more like Starbucks for people who hate corporatism than a real specialty coffeeshop.

Summit straddles the line between being that interesting-looking coffeeshop families who don't know any better go to as a treat, and being a cultural brand that also tries to make and serve its own coffee.

And I think that's where the issue lies: Summit is more concerned about upholding and presenting its brand, culture, and image than upholding standards and presenting a beautiful cup of coffee.

Go somewhere else, or if you absolutely have to go to Summit, get tea.

reviews_data.review_text:
I really didn't want to write this review.

I've been to Summit plenty of times over the past several years - probably since their inception - in fact, we used to buy Summit coffee in bulk for events years ago, and despite the poor quality of that coffee, this review will only pertain to this coffeeshop in Huntersville.

Summit coffee has consistently provided boring, bland, and awful tasting coffee throughout every visit I've had to this coffeeshop. The espresso is overextracted and violently bitter, while the filter coffee is weak, tasting more of commodity-grade coffee with unsweetened cherry flavor added to it. I have never had a good cup of coffee from Summit.

I get it though, the vibes are nice, it's a good place to hang out or study or work, I suppose. But I can do that many other places and enjoy much better coffee while doing so.

Staff is generally friendly enough, but baristas and hosts rarely have a deep knowledge or understanding of the roasts they are serving. Summit seems more like Starbucks for people who hate corporatism than a real specialty coffeeshop.

Summit straddles the line between being that interesting-looking coffeeshop families who don't know any better go to as a treat, and being a cultural brand that also tries to make and serve its own coffee.

And I think that's where the issue lies: Summit is more concerned about upholding and presenting its brand, culture, and image than upholding standards and presenting a beautiful cup of coffee.

Go somewhere else, or if you absolutely have to go to Summit, get tea.
